\b0\fs24 \

\b\fs30 History has already persuaded many of you \up2 about the first limita- \up0 tion. As noted earlier, the failure of cheap money policies was \up2 a \up0 major source of the reaction against simple-minded Keynesianism. \up2 In the \up0 United \dn3 States, \up0 this reaction involved widespread recognition that \up2 the \up0 wartime and postwar pegging of bond prices \up2 was a \up0 mistake, \up2 that the \dn3 abandonment \up0 of this policy was a desirable and inevitable step, \up2 and \dn3 that \up0 it hiadnone of the disturbing and disastrous consequences \up2 that \up0 were so freely predicted \up2 at the time. 
