\b\fs30 But how long, you will say, is "temporary"?For interest rates, we have some systematic evidence on how long each of the several effects takes to work itself out. For unemployment,we do not. I can at most venture a personal judgment, based on some examination of the histori- cal evidence, that the initial effects of a higher and unanticipated rate of inflation last for something like two to five years; that this initial effect then begins to be reversed; and that a full adjustment to the new rate of inflation takes about as long for employment as for interest \dn3 rates, say, \up0 a couple of decades. For both interest rates and employment, let me add a qualification. These estimates are for changes in the rate of inflation of the order of magnitude that has been experienced in the United States. For much more sizable changes, such as those experi- enced in South American countries, the whole adjustment process is greatly speeded up. 
