\b\fs30 By setting itself a steady course and keeping to it, the monetary au- thority could make a major contribution to promoting economic stabil- ity. By making that course one of steady but moderate growth in the quantity of money, it would make a major contributionto avoidance of either inflation or deflation of prices. Other forces would still affect the economy, require change and adjustment,and disturb the even tenor of our ways. But steady monetary growth would provide a monetary cli- mate favorable to the effective operation of those basic forces of enter- prise, ingenuity, invention, hard work, and thrift that are the true springs of economic growth. That is the most that we can ask from monetary policy at our present stage of knowledge. But that much- and it is a great deal-is clearly within our reach. }